<p class="p">We formulate the model description to address the above decision-making procedure. Let 
 <bold class="bold">x</bold>(
 <italic class="italic">t</italic>) and 
 <bold class="bold">a</bold> be the control variable at time 
 <italic class="italic">t</italic> and parameter with uncertainty, respectively. We define the uncertainty as a set of discrete scenarios 
 <italic class="italic">S</italic> = {
 <italic class="italic">s</italic>}, where each scenario s has a probability 
 <italic class="italic">P</italic>(
 <italic class="italic">s</italic>) at 
 <italic class="italic">t</italic> = 0 and 
 <bold class="bold">a</bold>(
 <italic class="italic">s</italic>) represents the parameter 
 <bold class="bold">a</bold> in a scenario s. The objective function to be maximized is represented by 
 <italic class="italic">f</italic>(
 <bold class="bold">x</bold>(
 <italic class="italic">t</italic>) | 
 <bold class="bold">a</bold>(
 <italic class="italic">s</italic>)). If the perfect ex ante information is available at 
 <italic class="italic">t</italic> = 0, then we need only to determine the optimal decision under the certain scenario 
 <italic class="italic">s</italic>
 <sup class="sup">*</sup>. This is represented by the case (a) of Fig. 
 <xref rid="Fig2" ref-type="fig" class="xref">2</xref>. The optimal behavior 
 <bold class="bold">
